Certainly! In LaTeX, generating a table of contents (ToC) is straightforward. Below is an example of how to create a simple document with an automatically generated table of contents:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

% For custom styling of ToC (optional), you might use packages like tocloft or titletoc
% Here, we'll keep it simple.

\begin{document}

% Title and author information
\title{Sample Document with Table of Contents}
\author{Your Name}
\maketitle

% Command to create the table of contents
\tableofcontents

% Start of the main document content
\newpage % This line ensures the content starts on a new page after the ToC

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\subsection{Background}
Here we discuss the background.

\section{Methodology}
Explanation of the methods used.

\subsection{Data Analysis}
Details on how data was analyzed.

\section{Results}
The findings are presented here.

\subsection{Discussion}
A discussion of the results.

\section{Conclusion}
Final thoughts and conclusions.

\appendix % For appendices
\section{Appendix A}
Additional material.

\section{Appendix B}
More additional material.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is used to automatically generate the table of contents. LaTeX will pick up on any `\section`, `\subsection`, etc., commands you use throughout your document and use them to populate the table of contents. Remember to run LaTeX two or more times to ensure the page numbers in the table of contents are correct, as the information is first written to an auxiliary file and then read back in during subsequent compilations.

